{
  "texts": [
    "By contrast, ∂φ(z) is regular near the W (u α) insertions.",
    "Integrating ∂φ(z) around a contour at z = 0 which excludes the vertex operators and zeroes of ξ + (z) gives the expression (5.1).",
    "An unexpected global symmetryWe noted earlier in section 2.4 that the Wakimoto fields (2.21) have OPEs generated by the action 34S = - 1 4π d 2 z 4∂Φ ∂Φ + β ∂γ.Naively, it appears that this action contains a global symmetry associated to radial translations, Φ → Φ + α for constant α, generated by the chargeK = 2 dz ∂Φ.As we may see by adding a Fradkin-Tseytlin termS = - 1 4π d 2 z 4∂Φ ∂Φ + β ∂γ + qRΦ, (5.9)on a curved worldsheet, this symmetry is potentially anomalous.",
    "In particular, the action changes as [32] δK S = - qα 4π d 2 z √ hR(h) = -2qα(1 -g).",
    "34 Whilst we choose to work with the perspective of free fields with operator insertions via (2.27), the following considerations would equally hold for (2.24) in a large Φ limit."
